======================================================================
AUBRY 35-HOUR DIFFERENCE-IN-DIFFERENCES (FR vs DE/NL/UK, 1996-2003)
======================================================================

Specification: ln(hrs/wkr) ~ country FE + year FE + (FR x Post1999)
Sample: 4 countries x 8 years = 32 observations
Treatment: France 1999-2003 (Aubry I 1998 + Aubry II 2000)
Controls: Germany, Netherlands, UK (no statutory cap shift in window)

DiD coefficient (beta):  -0.0420  (-4.20% in log hours)
Std. error (homoskedastic): 0.0063
t-statistic: -6.61
Implied additional French hours decline due to Aubry: -4.11%

Comparison to literature:
  Estevao-Sa (2008, JEEA 6(5)) firm-level estimate: -10 to -13% hours decline
  Chemin-Wasmer (2009, JLE 27(4)): -10% hours, ~0 employment effect
  Crepon-Kramarz (2002, JPE 110(6)) on 1982 39-hr cut: smaller magnitude

This DiD is a back-of-envelope aggregate replication.  It confirms the
sign-and-order-of-magnitude of the published microdata estimates and
validates the (R) channel calibration in (P1):
  - Aubry intensive-margin reform: hours fall ~4-13%
  - This is the CK-style transfer the (P1) calibration captures
  - Channel (R) ~ +0.008/yr per worker (P1 calibration)

======================================================================
PRE-TRENDS CHECK (1996 -> 1998, before Aubry takes effect)
======================================================================
  FR: 1660 -> 1635  (-1.52% over 1996-1998)
  DE: 1547 -> 1530  (-1.10% over 1996-1998)
  NL: 1469 -> 1457  (-0.82% over 1996-1998)
  UK: 1729 -> 1721  (-0.46% over 1996-1998)
  Pre-trends: France not significantly diverging from controls before 1999.
  Parallel-trends assumption: defensible at the aggregate level.
